There are two main approaches to the inverse solution: non-parametric and parametric methods. Non-parametric optimization methods are also referred to as Distributed Source Models, Distributed Inverse Solutions (DIS) or Imaging methods. In these models several dipole sources with fixed locations and possibly fixed orientations are distributed in the whole brain volume or cortical surface. As it is assumed that sources are intracellular currents in the dendritic trunks of the cortical pyramidal neurons, which are normally oriented to the cortical surface [6], fixed orientation dipoles are generally set to be normally aligned. The amplitudes (and direction) of these dipole sources are then estimated. Since the dipole location is not estimated the problem is a linear one. This means that in Equation 4, {
